# Camera, image, and performance rules

## Camera implementation bias

Prefer CameraX for capture flows.
Keep camera concerns isolated from general screen rendering and domain logic.

Do not create a giant camera screen that mixes:
- permission management
- camera binding
- image processing
- upload orchestration
- UI state modeling
- domain logic

## Image handling rules

Meal photos can be large and memory-heavy.

Always:
- avoid retaining full-size bitmaps longer than necessary
- prefer URI/file-reference based flows over giant in-memory objects
- resize/compress before upload according to backend requirements
- preserve enough quality for food recognition
- clean up temporary files when they are no longer needed
- model failure paths for blur, no image, or failed processing

Do not hardcode image dimensions unless product/backend requirements define them.

## Permission and failure handling

The user experience must gracefully handle:
- camera permission denied
- camera temporarily unavailable
- user canceling capture
- corrupted temp files
- upload failure after capture
- analysis failure after upload

Each of these should lead to a coherent user path, not a dead end.

## Performance rules

This is a mobile image-heavy app. Performance is part of product quality.

Avoid:
- heavy work on the main thread
- repeated decoding of the same image without need
- repeated identical analysis requests
- excessive recompositions in Compose
- long-lived giant objects in screen state

Prefer:
- background work for image processing
- stable and minimal UI state
- lazy lists for history
- bounded memory use
- careful cleanup of temporary resources

Do not prematurely micro-optimize, but do address obvious mobile bottlenecks.
